annotations.title: Understanding confidence intervals
annotations.text: You fit the model $Y_i=b_0+b_1X_i+e_i$ to your data an get a $b_1$ estimate of 2.0. But what is the true value of $\beta_0$ in the population? A confidence interval gives you a range of possible $\beta_1$s that could have generated the true $b_1$.

annotations.title: Where is the true $\beta_1$?
annotations.text: It could be 2.0. But it also could be a little lower or higher than that.

annotations.title: But could it be this low?
And could it be this high?
We need a sampling distribution
annotations.text: To figure out how low or high the true $\beta_1$ might be we need a sampling distribution, which shows us how loosely or tightly clustered the possible $b_1$s are around the true $\beta_1$.

annotations.title: Generating a sampling distribution
annotations.text: Lets construct a sampling distribution using the shuffle function. It will be centered around a $\beta_1$ of 0 -- simulating the empty model.

annotations.title: Build up a sampling distribution
annotations.text: We can build up a sampling distribution by randomly simulating multiple $b_1$s from a distribution centered at $\beta_1=0$.

annotations.title: Many random $b_1$s result in a sampling distribution
annotations.text: Let's draw 1000 random samples from the sampling distribution of $b_1$.
